metadata.name: Lucky Oracles #701
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/ Official Twitter account: https://twitter.com/eko3316 Official Instagram account: https://www.instagram.com/eko33studio/ https://linktr.ee/eko33 "I create deterministic generative art based on crypto hash seeds. Maximizing algorithmic diversity."

If you want to receive an e-mail alert when I release new artwork subscribe here => https://eko33.com/email-alerts

metadata.name: VOYAGERS #117
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from looping gestures in a virtual void.

Voyagers is an exploration of automated gestures and screenspace layering effects. Each brush stroke sweeps through the canvas leaving a trail of color that either disappears or mixes with adjacent colors. The image slowly builds up to achieve an equilibrium between the rhythm of the gestures and the interaction of color values. These colors are quantized and dithered to produce chunky, textured, blocks of light that reify the materiality of the screen and the pixel. Two aspect ratios are possible, each with its own material relationship to screen-based work, 1:1 and 4:3 (vertical).

Press 's' to save looping animated GIF (live mode only).
Press 'p' to pause the animation.
Press 'c' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: INSTRUCTURES #393
metadata.description:
Instructures explores the endless and diverse outcomes when a minimal and straightforward set of instructions are followed to build structures out of cubes. Between 4 and 8 instructions are selected and used to generate a unique structure for each edition. The available instructions are “stack”, “pile”, “plane” and “sculpt”. As a last step, flat and/or rounded corner details are optionally added to each structure.

Each artwork includes the set of instructions that were followed to build the structure. These instructions can be followed to build new structures using other methods in addition to programming, e.g. sculpting, printing, drawing, painting etc., and I plan on using this body of work to do exactly that. This project is, in fact, the result of an algorithm initially developed to generate interesting compositions and structures out of cubes to be used as points of departure for drawings, prints and paintings.

Even though the algorithm is focused on generating unique structures, the additional variations in scale, composition, colour, viewing angle and drawing style create an even wider array of generative outcomes. Some outputs are recognisable as three-dimensional orthographic drawings while others are more abstract. Instructures attempts to strike a balance between traditional art and the more technical nature of computer and blockchain art by blending visual cues from both disciplines. My hope is that the works can be appreciated by audiences from both of these worlds.

“The idea becomes a machine that makes the art.” — Sol Lewitt

Hotkeys
=======
Each artwork is interactive allowing the viewer to rotate, move and zoom in on the structure.

[H]elp — Complete list of available hotkeys
[I]nstructions – Instructions for structure
[F]eatures
[P]rint sizes
[Right click, save] – Save PNG image

[Z]oom
[W] Move up
[S] Move down
[A] Move left
[D] Move right
[<] Rotate clockwise
[>] Rotate anti-clockwise

Original artwork by Herman Pretorius, 2022

metadata.name: Tessellatum #23
metadata.description:
Tessellatum – a collection inspired by mosaic and weaving craftworks.

The artworks were created by applying a p5.js generative algorithm simulating mosaic, pointillism and weaving-like textures on a library of images issued/exported from a generative flowfield algorithm in R (The R Project for Statistical Computing). In other words, to avoid any ambiguity, the R issued images on which the mosaics effects are applied are not generated on the fxhash platform, but the mosaic effects (noise, size and shape of the tiles), the backgrounds and various other generative elements are via a p5.js implementation.

metadata.name: Waver #15
metadata.description:
Each mint is audioreactive visuals paired with a beat that’s composed from a selection of audio tracks, all based on the transaction hash

The six “instruments” in this beat are features that pull from a set of possible variants. The beat that you end up with when you mint is layered together from those features: there’s 5x5x4x4x4x2 possibilities for the audio which is, like, a lot of possibilities

All of those audio tracks are composed by hand the old-fashioned human-made way using sampling, synths, soul, and Ableton Live

The visuals are driven by the instruments in the beat, the colors are straight up random, and the whole visual output is modified by another set of features that modulate resolution and lo-fi vibes

Click to toggle playing, and to see what rad visual moments you can pause the beat on

P5.js + chroma.js + Tone.js + beats

metadata.name: Fält #33
metadata.description:
Fält is a study of shape, colour and texture. Designed to bring joy to the viewer, this is a work to light up the darkness of winter and awake feelings of curiosity. 

The series is controlled by a large number of random processes, from recursive subdivision with tweaks through Chaikin smoothing of the resulting polygons to mild domain warping of the entire canvas. Finally each shape is filled using small shapes, creating a warm and soft feel. 

Some features are tracked, but many are hidden in the resulting visuals, which will make exploration of the final collection surprising and rewarding.

metadata.name: Zaratan #114
metadata.description:
The Generative Token chooses between three primitives (cubes, spheres, triangle stripes) and places it along a parametric curve with parameters varying with noise() function as source of smooth motion.

New shapes are added layer after layer with new forms and colors.

At any time the user can pause the generation by pressing 'p', resume it with 'r' and save a 1600x1600 png with 's'.

Sources of variations are:
- primitives choice (3)
- orientation (0, 90, 180, 270 degrees)
- initial conditions
- shapes evolution
- colors evolution (only 10% will be bi-chromatic)


Press:
- 'p' to pause
- 'r' to resume
- 's' to save a 1600x1600 png image

metadata.name: Sigil Magic I #21
metadata.description:
Sigil Magic is personal, creative magic. The magic of chaos, of anarchy, self directed, unconventional. 
Each piece has a magical connection as denoted by one of ten colour palettes, each equally probable: Spirit, Fire, Faith, Water, Light, Earth, Ice, Stone, Metal and Plant.
Each piece has the potential to have design elements in each of eight compass directions. 
Each design element has its own connections - to masculine, feminine and neutral energy, to health, wealth strength and so on, which means there is great nuance of meaning for each complete Sigil. 
If you wish to receive an intuitive reading on a piece you have minted, please dm me on Twitter or Discord - Kusamehewa#5288

metadata.name: FUTURE BASTARDS #468
Planetary Abstracts #222
metadata.description:
A hazy planet looms large in an alien solar system. The image is "drawn" over 1,000 iterations with colored pencils on textured paper. The final image takes about 40-50 seconds.

The image size is 1200x1200. Press 's' to save a screenshot or 'p' to pause and resume drawing.

Common features:
- 50 color palettes
- Planet size, full view to partial
- 3 to 8 moons
- 2 noise methods
- 4 color modes
- 3 focus areas (line thickness)
- Vertical or horizontal accent bars

Uncommon
- Monochrome color palette
- Mono with color highlights
- Mono with gold highlights

Rare
- Mono with dark background

metadata.name: Zeno-Wheels #27
metadata.description:
Mint a random race car with stats; Speed, Acceleration and Steering.
You can see your stats in order below the car.
The side colors of the background determine how rare your car is.
 - Uncommon - White
 - Common - Green
 - Rare - Blue
 - Epic - Purple 
 - Legendary - Orange

But that's not all! Press the play button to actually lap test your minted car!
Every car plays on the same race track.
On theory you should have the same lap time on every run with the same mint.

You can also take a screenshot with the camera button in the menu or when you finish a lap.
*IMPORTANT* You have to be in live view (bottom right corner says 'open live') to save a screenshots!

Tweet @Zenobyl screenshot of your mint.

Good luck drivers!
